:::
::::

</div>

## Axiom 3: Monotonicity ("More is Better") :arrow_up:

<div style="font-size: 85%;">

::: {.key-concept}
**Monotonicity**

If bundle $A$ has **at least as much** of every good as $B$, and **strictly more** of at least one good, then $A \succ B$.
:::

**In plain language**: More of a good thing is always preferred, all else equal.

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
:white_check_mark: **Example**:

$(4 \text{ meals}, 3 \text{ museums}) \succ (3 \text{ meals}, 3 \text{ museums})$

Same museums, one extra meal :arrow_right: strictly better
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
:bulb: **Implication**:

This rules out "bads" (things you'd rather have less of, like pollution)

For this course, we assume all goods are **desirable**.
:::
::::

</div>

# Indifference Curves

## What Is an Indifference Curve? :wavy_dash:

<div style="font-size: 85%;">

::: {.key-concept}
**Indifference Curve**

The set of all bundles that give the consumer the **same level of satisfaction**.

Along an indifference curve: $A \sim B$ for all points $A, B$ on the curve.
:::

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Tourism intuition**:

A tourist might be equally happy with:

- 5 beach days + 1 cultural tour
- 3 beach days + 3 cultural tours
- 1 beach day + 6 cultural tours

All on the **same** indifference curve!
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
:point_right: The consumer is **indifferent** between any two points on the same curve.

Moving to a **higher** curve = **better** (by monotonicity).

Moving to a **lower** curve = **worse**.
:::
::::

</div>

## Drawing Indifference Curves :art:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 11
#| fig-height: 5.5
#| fig-align: center

# Standard convex indifference curves (Cobb-Douglas style: x2 = k/x1)
x1_vals <- seq(0.5, 8, length.out = 200)

df_ic <- bind_rows(
  data.frame(x1 = x1_vals, x2 = 4 / x1_vals, curve = "U₁ (lower)"),
  data.frame(x1 = x1_vals, x2 = 9 / x1_vals, curve = "U₂ (medium)"),
  data.frame(x1 = x1_vals, x2 = 16 / x1_vals, curve = "U₃ (higher)")
)

# Points on U2
pts <- data.frame(
  x1 = c(1.5, 3, 6),
  x2 = c(6, 3, 1.5),
  label = c("A", "B", "C")
)

ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = df_ic, aes(x = x1, y = x2, color = curve, linetype = curve),
            linewidth = 1.6) +
  geom_point(data = pts, aes(x = x1, y = x2), size = 4, color = ue_black) +
  geom_text(data = pts, aes(x = x1, y = x2, label = label),
            vjust = -1, size = 5.5, fontface = "bold", color = ue_black) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(ue_gray, ue_red, ue_black)) +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c("dashed", "solid", "dashed")) +
  annotate("segment", x = 5, y = 5, xend = 6.5, yend = 6,
           arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.3, "cm")), color = ue_red, linewidth = 1) +
  annotate("text", x = 6.3, y = 4.5, label = "Higher\nsatisfaction", size = 4.5,
