```

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

Points $A$, $B$, $C$ are on the **same** curve ($U_2$): the tourist is **indifferent** among them.

</div>

## Properties of Indifference Curves

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

The axioms imply **four key properties**:

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
:one: **Higher curves are preferred**

(monotonicity: more is better)

:two: **Downward sloping**

(to stay indifferent, getting more of one good requires giving up some of the other)
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
:three: **Cannot cross**

(would violate transitivity — we'll prove this next!)

:four: **Exactly one curve through every point**

(completeness: every bundle belongs to some indifference level)
:::
::::

</div>

## Why Can't Indifference Curves Cross? :x:

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

**Proof by contradiction** (using the axioms):

</div>

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 9
#| fig-height: 4.5
#| fig-align: center

# Two crossing indifference curves - showing the contradiction
x1_v <- seq(0.5, 7, length.out = 200)

df_cross <- bind_rows(
  data.frame(x1 = x1_v, x2 = 8 / x1_v, curve = "IC₁"),
  data.frame(x1 = x1_v, x2 = 1.5 + 6 / x1_v, curve = "IC₂")
)

# Crossing point approx at x1=3, x2=8/3≈2.67 and 1.5+6/3=3.5 -- not exact
# Better: use x2 = 8/x1 and x2 = 12/x1 + a shift to create a clear cross
# Simpler approach: IC1: x2 = 12/x1, IC2 shifted to cross
# Let me use: IC1: x2=8/x1, IC2: x2=0.5+6/x1. Cross at 8/x1=0.5+6/x1 -> 2/x1=0.5 -> x1=4, x2=2
df_cross <- bind_rows(
  data.frame(x1 = x1_v, x2 = 8 / x1_v, curve = "IC₁"),
  data.frame(x1 = x1_v, x2 = 0.5 + 6 / x1_v, curve = "IC₂")
)

# Cross at (4, 2). Pick X=(4,2) on both, Y on IC1 only, Z on IC2 only
# IC1 at x1=2: x2=4. IC2 at x1=2: x2=0.5+3=3.5.
# So Y=(2,4) on IC1, Z=(2,3.5) on IC2
cross_pts <- data.frame(
  x1 = c(4, 2, 2),
  x2 = c(2, 4, 3.5),
  label = c("X", "Y", "Z")
)

ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = df_cross, aes(x = x1, y = x2, color = curve),
            linewidth = 1.8) +
  geom_point(data = cross_pts, aes(x = x1, y = x2),
             size = 5, color = ue_black) +
    geom_text(
    data = cross_pts,
    aes(
      x = x1, y = x2, label = label,
      vjust = ifelse(label == "Z", 2, -1.2)  # Z below, others above
    ),
    size = 6, fontface = "bold", color = ue_black
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(ue_red, ue_gray)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 7), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(x = expression(x[1]), y = expression(x[2]),
       title = "If indifference curves crossed...",
       color = "") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 16) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = ue_red, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5, size = 18),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14),
    legend.position = c(0.85, 0.85),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = ue_gray),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )
```

<div style="font-size: 78%;">

- $X$ and $Y$ are on $IC_1$ :arrow_right: $X \sim Y$
- $X$ and $Z$ are on $IC_2$ :arrow_right: $X \sim Z$
- By **transitivity**: $Y \sim Z$
- But $Y = (2, 4)$ has more of $x_2$ than $Z = (2, 3.5)$ (same $x_1$) :arrow_right: **monotonicity** says $Y \succ Z$ :boom: **Contradiction!**

</div>

## Axiom 4: Convexity

<div style="font-size: 82%;">

::: {.key-concept}
**Convexity**

Averages (mixtures) of bundles are **at least as good** as extremes.

If $A \sim B$, then any weighted average $\lambda A + (1-\lambda) B$ is weakly preferred ($\succsim A$), where $0 < \lambda < 1$.
:::

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Intuition**: People prefer **balanced** consumption to extremes.

A tourist equally happy with:

- 7 beach days + 0 museums
- 0 beach days + 7 museums

Would **prefer** 3.5 beach + 3.5 museums!
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
**Graphically**: Indifference curves are **bowed toward the origin** (convex shape).

:point_right: This will give us a **diminishing** Marginal Rate of Substitution (Lecture 7)
:::
::::

</div>

## Convexity: Graphical Intuition :chart_with_downwards_trend:

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 11
#| fig-height: 5
#| fig-align: center

# Show convexity: average of two extreme points is preferred
x1_cv <- seq(0.3, 8, length.out = 300)
ic_cv <- 6 / x1_cv  # IC through (1,6) and (6,1)

df_cv <- data.frame(x1 = x1_cv, x2 = ic_cv)

# Extreme points on the curve
pt_A <- data.frame(x1 = 1, x2 = 6)
pt_B <- data.frame(x1 = 6, x2 = 1)
# Average point
pt_avg <- data.frame(x1 = 3.5, x2 = 3.5)

ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = df_cv, aes(x = x1, y = x2), color = ue_red, linewidth = 2) +
  # Dashed line connecting A and B
  geom_segment(aes(x = 1, y = 6, xend = 6, yend = 1),
               linetype = "dashed", color = ue_gray, linewidth = 1) +
  # Points
  geom_point(data = pt_A, aes(x = x1, y = x2), size = 5, color = ue_black) +
  geom_point(data = pt_B, aes(x = x1, y = x2), size = 5, color = ue_black) +
  geom_point(data = pt_avg, aes(x = x1, y = x2), size = 6, color = ue_red,
             shape = 18) +
  # Labels
  annotate("text", x = 0.5, y = 6.4, label = "A (extreme)", size = 5,
           fontface = "bold", color = ue_black) +
  annotate("text", x = 6.5, y = 0.6, label = "B (extreme)", size = 5,
           fontface = "bold", color = ue_black) +
  annotate("text", x = 3.5, y = 4.1, label = "Average\n(preferred!)", size = 5,
           fontface = "bold", color = ue_red) +
  # Arrow to show "above the IC"
  annotate("segment", x = 3.5, y = 3.5, xend = 3.5, yend = 6/3.5,
           arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.2, "cm"), ends = "first"),
           color = ue_red, linewidth = 0.8, linetype = "dotted") +
  annotate("text", x = 4.2, y = 2.3, label = "Same IC as\nA and B", size = 4,
           color = ue_red, fontface = "italic") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8), expand = c(0, 0), breaks = 0:8) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 8), expand = c(0, 0), breaks = 0:8) +
  labs(x = expression(x[1]), y = expression(x[2]),
       title = "Convexity: Mixtures Are Preferred to Extremes") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 16) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = ue_red, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5, size = 18),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )
```

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

The average of $A$ and $B$ lies **above** the indifference curve :arrow_right: it is on a **higher** curve :arrow_right: preferred!

</div>

## Summary of the Four Axioms

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

| Axiom | Statement | Intuition |
|:--|:--|:--|
| **Completeness** | Can always compare any two bundles | No indecision paralysis |
| **Transitivity** | If $A \succsim B$ and $B \succsim C$, then $A \succsim C$ | No preference cycles |
| **Monotonicity** | More of a good is better | Goods are desirable |
| **Convexity** | Mixtures preferred to extremes | Variety is valued |

</div>

:point_right: If these hold, preferences can be represented by a **utility function** $U(x_1, x_2)$ — that's Lecture 7!

:point_right: The utility function assigns a **number** to each bundle so that higher numbers = preferred bundles.

# Special Cases

## Special Case 1: Perfect Substitutes :left_right_arrow:

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Definition**: Consumer is willing to trade goods at a **constant rate**.

Indifference curves are **straight lines**.

**Tourism example**: A tourist is indifferent between a €10 lunch voucher and €10 cash — they substitute perfectly at a 1:1 rate.
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 5
#| fig-height: 4.5
#| fig-align: center

df_ps <- bind_rows(
  data.frame(x1 = c(0, 4), x2 = c(4, 0), ic = "U₁"),
  data.frame(x1 = c(0, 6), x2 = c(6, 0), ic = "U₂"),
  data.frame(x1 = c(0, 8), x2 = c(8, 0), ic = "U₃")
)

ggplot(df_ps, aes(x = x1, y = x2, color = ic)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(ue_gray, ue_red, ue_black)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 9), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 9), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(x = expression(x[1]), y = expression(x[2]),
       title = "Perfect Substitutes", color = "") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = ue_red, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.position = c(0.85, 0.85),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = ue_gray),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )
```
:::
::::

:bulb: **No** convexity here — the consumer doesn't care about "balance."

</div>

## Special Case 2: Perfect Complements :jigsaw:

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Definition**: Goods are always consumed in **fixed proportions**.

Indifference curves are **L-shaped** (right angles).

**Tourism example**: A ski pass and ski rental — having 3 ski passes and 1 ski rental is no better than having 1 of each (you need both to ski!).
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
#| fig-width: 5
#| fig-height: 4.5
#| fig-align: center

# L-shaped indifference curves
df_pc <- bind_rows(
  # U1: kink at (2,2)
  data.frame(x1 = c(2, 2), x2 = c(8, 2), seg = "v1", ic = "U₁"),
  data.frame(x1 = c(2, 8), x2 = c(2, 2), seg = "h1", ic = "U₁"),
  # U2: kink at (4,4)
  data.frame(x1 = c(4, 4), x2 = c(8, 4), seg = "v2", ic = "U₂"),
  data.frame(x1 = c(4, 8), x2 = c(4, 4), seg = "h2", ic = "U₂"),
  # U3: kink at (6,6)
  data.frame(x1 = c(6, 6), x2 = c(8, 6), seg = "v3", ic = "U₃"),
  data.frame(x1 = c(6, 8), x2 = c(6, 6), seg = "h3", ic = "U₃")
)

kink_pts <- data.frame(x1 = c(2, 4, 6), x2 = c(2, 4, 6),
                        ic = c("U₁", "U₂", "U₃"))

ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = df_pc, aes(x = x1, y = x2, group = seg, color = ic),
            linewidth = 1.5) +
  geom_point(data = kink_pts, aes(x = x1, y = x2, color = ic), size = 4) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(ue_gray, ue_red, ue_black)) +
  # 45-degree line through kinks
  geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = 7.5, yend = 7.5),
               linetype = "dotted", color = ue_gray, linewidth = 0.8) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 9), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 9), expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(x = expression("Ski passes (" * x[1] * ")"),
       y = expression("Ski rentals (" * x[2] * ")"),
       title = "Perfect Complements", color = "") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = ue_red, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.position = c(0.85, 0.85),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = ue_gray),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )
```
:::
::::

:bulb: More of one good **without** the other gives **no** extra satisfaction.

</div>

## The "Normal" Case :thumbsup:

<div style="font-size: 82%;">

Most goods lie **between** the two extremes:

| Type | IC Shape | Substitutability | Example |
|:--|:-:|:-:|:--|
| Perfect Substitutes | Straight line | Complete | €10 cash vs €10 voucher |
| **Normal goods** | **Smooth convex curve** | **Partial** | **Beach days vs cultural tours** |
| Perfect Complements | L-shape | None | Ski pass + ski rental |

</div>

:point_right: For the rest of this course, unless stated otherwise, we assume the **normal** case: smooth, convex, downward-sloping indifference curves.

This is where **convexity** applies — consumers value variety and are willing to trade goods, but at a **changing** rate. That changing rate will be the **MRS** in Lecture 7!

# Tourism Application

## Tourism: Revealed Preferences :airplane:

<div style="font-size: 80%;">

**How do we know tourist preferences in practice?**

We can't read minds — but we can observe **choices**!

:::: {.columns}
::: {.column width="50%"}
**Revealed preference logic**:

If a tourist *could afford* both packages A and B, but *chose* A, then:

$$A \succsim B$$

Their choice **reveals** their preference!
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
**Tourism industry applications**:

- :computer: Booking data reveals preferences for destinations, hotel stars, trip lengths
- :bar_chart: A/B testing on travel websites reveals what tourists click on
- :airplane: Airline loyalty programs track revealed choices over time
:::
::::

:bulb: This is why tourism companies collect **so much data** — they're mapping your indifference curves!

</div>

## Summary: Today's Key Takeaways

<div style="font-size: 78%;">

**Today's Lecture**:

1. **Preferences** rank bundles — independently of prices or income
2. **Four axioms** make preferences "rational" and modelable:
   - **Completeness**: always able to compare
   - **Transitivity**: no preference cycles
   - **Monotonicity**: more is better
   - **Convexity**: mixtures preferred to extremes
3. **Indifference curves**: connect bundles giving equal satisfaction
4. IC properties: downward-sloping, don't cross, higher = better, convex
5. **Special cases**: perfect substitutes (lines) and perfect complements (L-shapes)

**Connection to Lecture 5**: Budget constraint shows what's *feasible*; preferences show what's *desirable*.

**Next (Lecture 7)**: The **Marginal Rate of Substitution** (the slope of the IC) and **utility functions** — how we turn preferences into math and find the **optimal choice**!

</div>

